Bibliometric analysis of Thaler, R. H., & Benartzi, S. (2004). Save more tomorrow™: Using behavioral economics to increase employee saving. Journal of political Economy, 112(S1), S164-S187.

Author

Marton Kovacs

Setup

# Loading packages
library(bibliometrix)
library(here)
library(kableExtra)
library(tidyverse)

# Loading data
data_file <- here::here("data/savedrecs.bib")

## Converting the bibtex exported data to a bibliographic dataframe
data <- convert2df(file = data_file, dbsource = "wos", format = "bibtex")

Converting your wos collection into a bibliographic dataframe

Done!


Generating affiliation field tag AU_UN from C1:  Done!

Creating the collection

To create the collection we used the Clarivate Analytics Web of Science database to search for all the citation to the seminal paper of Thaler, R. H., & Benartzi, S. (2004). Save more tomorrow™: Using behavioral economics to increase employee saving. Journal of political Economy, 112(S1), S164-S187.

We narrowed our search by the Web of Science Index filter to only include citations from the Social Sciences Citation Index (SSCI) and the Science Citation Index Expanded (SCI-EXPANDED). Thus, we do not inlcude any books, conference proceedings, and citations from the Arts & Humanities Citation Index.

The refined search returned 810 citations on the 3rd of January 2025.

We decided to export all the available data to a bibtex file for our analysis.

Bibliometric analysis

results <- biblioAnalysis(data, sep = ";")

Ensure that all the papers that cite our target article are in the dataframe. There should be 810 manuscripts in our collection.

results$Articles
[1] 810

Create summary tables of the results.

options(width=100)
summary_tables <- summary(object = results, k = 10, pause = FALSE, verbose = FALSE)

Create summary plots of the descriptive results.

summary_plots <- plot(x = results, k = 10, pause = FALSE, verbose = FALSE)

Based on Table 1 it seems that most documents citing the target article are between 2004 and 2025. On average the documents are cited 44.07 times. The number of documents published that cite our target article is on the decline as suggested by the annual growth rate -1.91. This could be due to the fact that we run the analysis at the beginning of a new year. Most documents in our collection are articles (n = 727).

Figure 1 shows the average number of total citations of the papers in our collection. Based on the figure it seems that the papers citing our target paper are also influential, gaining more than 50 citations on average bafore 2016. However, it seems that their influence is on a decreasing trend after that signaling that they are loosing attention over time.

summary_plots$AverTotCitperYear

Fig. 1. The figure shows the average citations of the papers in our collection since the publication of the target paper.

By looking at Table 2 we can see no substantial drop in the number of documents published over the years, which indicates that the target paper is still influential to this day. The same pattern can be seen on Figure 2. Based on Figure 1 and Figure 2 it seems that while the target article is still being cited even today the impact of the papers citing it is decreasing.

Fig. 3. The figure shows the most productive authors regarding our target article. The number of documents show the number of articles by these authors that cite our target article.

It seems that CHOI JJ is the most productive author who cited the target paper 8. The Artciles Fractionalized metrics show the most productive authors contribution weighted by the number of co-authors on their publictation. CHOI JJ is still the most productive author even if we take the number of co-authors into account.

Table 4 shows the H-indices of the most productive authors. This metric can be used to assess their influence in general, outside of the scope of the target article. The H-index is an author-level metric that attempts to measure both the productivity (number of articles published) and citation impact (number of citations) of the publications of a scientist or scholar.

Table 4 H-indices of the Most Productive Authors

Most cited papers

Table 5 shows the most cited papers in our collection. The most cited paper of LUSARDI A, 2014, J ECON LIT provides a general overview of the recent literature on financial literacy, exploring evidence based on survey studies and theoretical advancements in the area.

TC shows the Total Citations to the article, including the ones in the current collection.

The Normalized Total Citations (NTC) is calculated by dividing the total number of citations of an article by the average number of citations of all documents published in the same year; this measure takes into account differences in citation practices across disciplines and provides a more meaningful comparison of citation impact. (https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10073695/)[https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10073695/]

cr_article <- citations(data, field = "article", sep = ";")

Global citations means that total citations that an article, included in your collection, has received from documents indexed on WoS. In contrast,local citations measure how many times a document included in this collection have been cited by other documents also in the collection.

We can do topic analysis on the keywords of these documents. WoS provides “Keyword Plus” (ID tag) that many publications advice as the best content field to perform topic analysis (https://www.bibliometrix.org/home/index.php/faq)[https://www.bibliometrix.org/home/index.php/faq]. There are 1770 keywords of this kind.

To map the thematic structure using co-occurring keywords, we create the keyword co-occurrence network.

network_matrix <- biblioNetwork(data, analysis = "co-occurrences", 
                                network = "keywords", sep = ";")

Figure 6 shows the keyword co-occurance network. There are two distinct groups of keywords provided in our collection.

networkPlot(network_matrix, normalize = "association", 
            weighted = TRUE, n = 50, type = "auto", size = 5, labelsize = 1)

Three-field plot

We can depict the relation between three field keys using a three-field plot (Sankey diagram). For example, we can show the proportion of keywords for each country and the year of publication.

threeFieldsPlot(data, fields = c("DE","AU","CR"), n = c(20, 20, 20))
